From our answer in part i), the distance between the moose and the car
is given by d(t), where

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle d(t) = |-t^{2} + 8t - 12|.
\end{align*} To solve for the time when
the moose hits the car we solve the equation d(T) = 0 to get T.

\begin{align*}
d(T) = |-T^{2} + 8T - 12| &= 0 \\
|-(T - 6)(T - 2)| &= 0 \quad \rightarrow \quad T = 2,6
\end{align*} Since the moose will not hit the car twice, we choose the
smaller of the two times, and say the moose will hit the car at

\begin{align*}
{\color{blue}T =2.}
\end{align*}
